{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Gonja |image = |caption = |poptime = |popplace = [[Kingdom of Dagbon (Northern Territories)|Kingdom of Dagbon]], [[Northern Region (Ghana)|Northern region]], Ghana |region1 = Ghana |pop1 = |ref1 = |langs = [[Gonja language|Gonja]] |rels = [[Islam]] |related = subgroup of the [[Guang people]]}}
''This page discusses the Ghanaian kingdom of Gonja; for uses for the word Ganja, see [[Ganja (disambiguation)]]''
'''Gonja''' (also '''Ghanjawiyyu''') was a kingdom in northern [[Ghana]] founded in 1675 by [[Sumaila Ndewura Jakpa]].<ref name="relatives">{{Cite book |title=Native Peoples of the World: An Encyclopedia of Groups, Cultures and Contemporary Issues |last=Danver |first=Steven L. |publisher=Routledge |year=2015 |isbn=9781317464006 |publication-date=10 Mar 2015 |pages=34}}</ref> The word can also refer to the people of this kingdom.
==Origin== The Gonja are a [[Guan people]] who have been influenced by Akan, Mande and Hausa people. With the fall of the [[Songhai Empire]] (c. 1600), the [[Mandé peoples|Mande]] [[Ngbanya]] clan moved south, crossing the [[Black Volta]] and founding a city at [[Yagbum]]. The Gonja kingdom was originally divided into sections overseen by male siblings of Sumaila Ndewura Jakpa including their children and grandchildren.<ref name="relatives"/>
Under the leadership of [[Naba'a]], the Ngbanya dynasty of Gonja was founded. The capital was established at [[Yagbum]].<ref name="Bakewell">{{cite book|author=Wilks,Ivor. Wangara, Akan, and Portuguese in the Fifteenth and Sixteenth Centuries|editor1-last=Bakewell|editor1-first=Peter|title=Mines of Silver and Gold in the Americas|date=1997|publisher=Variorum, Ashgate Publishing Limited|location=Aldershot|pages=29–30}}</ref>
The Ngbanya expanded rapidly, conquering several neighbors in the [[White Volta]] valley and beginning a profitable gold trade with the [[Akan people|Akan states]] through nearby [[Begho]]. By 1675, the Gonja established a [[paramount chief]], called the [[Yagbongwura]], to control the kingdom. The Ngbanya dynasty has controlled this position from its founding to the present day, with only two brief [[interregnum]]s. The current Yagbongwura, ''Tuntumba Sulemana Jakpa Bore Essa'', has held his position since 2010. [[File:The National Archives UK - CO 1069-43-87-1-001.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Gonja chiefs and elders at the Volta River project travelling exhibition(1950)]] Precolonial Gonja society was stratified into [[caste]]s, with a ruling class, a [[Islam|Muslim]] trader class, an [[animist]] commoner class, and a [[slavery|slave]] class. Its economy depended largely on trade in [[African slave trade|slaves]] from Central Africa<ref>The Evolution of War: A Study of Its Role in Early SocietiesBy Maurice R. Davie</ref> and [[kola nut]]s, particularly through the market town of [[Salaga]], sometimes called the "[[Timbuktu]] of the South."
The [[Gonja language]] is a [[Tano languages|Tano language]] within the [[Kwa languages]] family, closely related to [[Akan languages]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w8vzkqDsv-IC&pg=PA4&dq=Central+Tano+languages&hl=en&ei=TwJdTdHBH8jKgQea3fm2DA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Central%20Tano%20languages&f=false Aspect and Modality in Kwa Languages]. books.google.com. [[Google Books]].</ref>
